Household tidying is a deeply personal activity shaped by individual habits, mental categories, and tacit organizing principles that users rarely articulate unprompted. When an intelligent agent assists with rearrangement, the central challenge is not \emph{what} to learn but \emph{how to ask}---whether to query individual object placements, elicit category-level rules, or confirm patterns inferred from prior evidence. Each questioning approach embodies a different assumption about users' ability and willingness to articulate preferences at varying levels of abstraction. We identify three complementary strategies operating at different granularities: \textbf{Action-Oriented} (AO) questioning targets individual placements, \textbf{Preference Eliciting} (PE) uncovers category-level organizing principles, and \textbf{Preference Induction} (PI) confirms rules inferred from accumulated evidence. We implement these strategies within an LLM-based conversational agent and investigate them through two studies. Study~1, a large-scale simulation across 102 household episodes at question budgets 0--6, establishes that structured questioning dramatically outperforms both no-question baselines and unstructured LLM querying, with PE achieving up to 71.9\% unseen-object accuracy versus 42.6\% without questioning. Study~2, a controlled user study currently underway, is designed to examine how strategies affect perceived control, cognitive load, and satisfaction. Guided by the simulation findings, we predict that the accuracy advantage of PE comes at the cost of reduced user sense of agency, and that individual differences in organizing expertise moderate which strategy users find most effective. We discuss theoretical implications for preference communication in human-agent interaction and offer design recommendations for conversational agents that actively learn from users.
